Just finished my first SUK. gloves, they don’t look too bad? They possibly need a bit of fine tuning :-)

We are told to wash hands often & put sanitizer gel on to keep our hands clean during this pandemic.

I don’t know whether I am the only one have got an issue of using any sanitizer gel, my skin just can’t cope.
With sensitive hands, there is also no luck with disposable plastic gloves neither, also I very much disagree with the concept of anything being disposable.

So I made a pair of organic cotton gloves, problem solved?

Have you got the same issue?

node.text: S fint skrivet och en pminnelse! ??
S fint skrivet och en pminnelse! ??

Pltsligt finns den dr, en liten stig mellan hallonsnren. Jag har gtt i omrdet i mnga r och idag var mina gon redo att se den. Jag undrar hur mycket mer jag ”inte ser” trots att det finns framfr mig varje dag. Pminner mig om att vi mnniskor vaknar andligt och mentalt i olika tider och p olika stt. Pandemin har varit en tid fr reflektion, att stilla mig i vardagens brus och upptcka livet p ett nytt stt. Aldrig har vardagens sysslor gett mig strre gldje n nu. Vindens sus i lvtrden, regnet som faller och jag fr vara torr inomhus, mat att tillaga och ta. Att f sova nr sinnet och kroppen r trtt. Varje dag r en gva, jag hade bara glmt det. S tack fr livet och vardagen!
.
Today I found it, a new pathway through the raspberry bushes, even thou I have walked by for so many years. Due to, or in my case thanks to the pandemic I have been able to be still in mind and body. Start to appreciate my every day life. My eyes were opened spiritually and mentally to this pathway, in a time when I was ready for it.
Today I am more grateful for every day chores, for the rain that falls and I can stay at home being dry and warm. To the gentle breeze in the trees and being able to fall asleep when mind and body are tired. Every day is a gift, I had forgotten. Thank you for life and every day life!
.

This is life as a parent in general. So much unsolicited advise, get a routine, go out for walks, leave them to cry, don’t bedshare, give him a bottle, wean early. So I can only imagine what people say to you around this subject. All I can say is you know what’s best for you, it very often comes from a good place but I often just smiled and nodded or said something (depending how sleep deprived I was haha). 
When my husband had to leave us in hospital I found that very traumatic and I didn’t have the added fear of a pandemic. I suffered trauma psychologically from that so goodness know how you feel. Sending lots of love. Xxx

BORN IN A PANDEMIC. When CeCe asks what it was like when she was born, I think this picture will show her more than I can describe. The pandemic has had a few benefits in the sense I feel I’ve really been able to spend time with my baby BUT it has also come at a price; husband leaving straight after the birth, grandparents not being able to see her for weeks, friends unable to cuddle her, not having a get together for her birth, not being able to do many baby classes or get her weighed! I do not feel hard done by. People are massively suffering in the world. However I’ve mostly found people’s opinions the hardest part of this situation, my close family and friends have been so supportive but why do other people think they can advise/suggest how you handle these unknown and unfamiliar times with your baby? Some call you crazy for not going out much and others warn you stay away from the outside world. Anyone else had a baby at this time and felt the same? Or just feel this way in general?!

node.text:
Who knew snorkels could be up-cycled to make PPE!? 

We've just received an update from our Project Leaders in Bangladesh who've been creating PPE and ventilators to support frontline medical staff and patients through Covid-19.  Long story short, they've taken secondhand snorkels and created PAPRs (Powered Air Purifying Respirator) - and they're extremely effective! Those interested in the fine print, read on!
...................

Hi Jo and Christey! So we had some key updates on our ventilator project.

Based on demand, supply shortages and our research we adapted the project in a very unique manner. 

We created PAPRs using snorkelling masks which can double as a full face respirator for frontliners which can easily replace their face mask, face shield with this reusable less wasteful and significantly better solution. Additionally the PAPR also doubles up as a ventilator mask which can be retrofitted to any CPAP or BiPAP machine commonly available to provide clean breathing support without having any chance any of the risks of the ambubag type we initially had. 

The design already has FDA emergency approval and is being used around the world. We adopted it in Bangladesh and customized it based on our own needs here. 

We are here and being able to support frontliners like never before because of all the funding we received for you guys. So now our ventilator project doubles up as PPE project for doctors too! We are just too excited to share this amazing news with you guys. 

www.justpeoples.org/covid-19
